# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: citroën-2cv
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:citroën-2cv/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The **1986 FIFA World Cup** was the 13th FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial football tournament for men's senior national teams.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] It was played in Mexico from 31 May to 29 June 1986.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The tournament was the second to feature a 24-team format.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Colombia had been originally chosen to host the competition by FIFA but, largely due to economic reasons, was not able to do so, and resigned in November 1982.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Mexico was selected as the new host in May 1983, and became the first country to host the World Cup more than once, after previously hosting the 1970 edition.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The World Cup was won by Argentina (their second title, after winning in 1978).
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Argentina was captained by the 25-year-old Diego Maradona, who played a large part in his team's success by scoring his "Hand of God" goal, as well as another voted the "Goal of the Century", in the same quarter-final match against England.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] These were two of the five goals that Maradona scored during the tournament, and he also created another five for his teammates.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Argentina beat West Germany 3–2 in the final at Mexico City's Estadio Azteca.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Argentina would not win the World Cup again until 2022, 36 years later.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Total attendance was 2,394,031, an average per match of 46,039.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Canada, Denmark and Iraq made their first appearances at the final stage.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The format of the competition changed from 1982.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The final pair of matches in each group started at the same time and the second round was played on a knockout basis rather than groups.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The 24 teams qualified were divided into six groups of four (A to F).
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The top two teams and the four best third-place finishers from the six groups advanced to the knockout round of 16 teams.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Italy were the defending champions, but were eliminated by France in the round of 16.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The tournament saw the appearance of the Mexican wave, a spectator phenomenon which was popularised worldwide after featuring during the tournament.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Colombia was originally chosen as hosts by FIFA in June 1974, with Bogotá, Medellín, Cali, Pereira and Bucaramanga intended as the host cities, plus potentially Barranquilla.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Colombia agreed to host a 16-team competition.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] However, days before the 1978 FIFA World Cup's opening match, FIFA later allowed an expansion to 24 teams for the 1982 World Cup in Spain, which was more challenging for Colombia to host, although FIFA President João Havelange initially gave assurances that they could revert to a 16-team tournament.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Colombian president Julio César Turbay Ayala was initially against holding the tournament in his country, but reluctantly granted permission in October 1980.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] However, the next Colombian president, Belisario Betancur, declared on 5 November 1982 that they could not afford to host the World Cup under the terms that FIFA demanded.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] On 20 May, the committee announced Mexico as the replacement hosts despite Havelange stating that the United States and Canada had made better presentations.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Mexico became the first nation to host two World Cups, as it had hosted the 1970 FIFA World Cup.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The Canadian representatives criticised the committee's decision not to consider Canada, saying they had submitted a more complete bid than Mexico, and that they had been misled by the number of stadiums required for bidding.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The United States' bid contained more than the required number of stadiums with the required capacity to host World Cup matches (at least 40,000 capacity, 60,000 for second-round matches and 80,000 for the tournament final).
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Mexico submitted a bid with 14 stadiums, only six of which seated over 40,000 at the time of the bid, and three over 60,000.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Havelange in turn criticised the United States' handling of stadium selection for the football tournament at the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The Americans also pointed out that Mexico had the influence of two seats on the 22-person executive committee, a FIFA vice president and an executive at Televisa, a Mexican television network with ties to Havelange.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Also working in Mexico's favour was Havelange secretly promising the broadcast rights to Televisa ahead of the vote.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] A severe earthquake in September 1985, eight months before the tournament, cast doubt over Mexico's ability to organise the event, but the stadiums were not affected and it was decided to go ahead with the preparations.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] As 1986 had been declared the International Year of Peace by the United Nations, the advertising boards of all the stadia displayed the FIFA and United Nations logos along with the legend "Football for Peace – Peace Year".
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] For the design of the logo an unofficial motto was adopted: "El Mundo Unido por Un Balón" ("The World United by a Ball").
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The final draw took place on 15 December 1985 hosted at Televisa San Ángel studios in Mexico City.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Three teams qualified for the World Cup for the first time: Canada, Denmark and Iraq.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Iraq played all their 'home' matches on neutral ground in Saudi Arabia because of the Iran–Iraq War.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Canada would not appear again until 2022, and Iraq would not qualify again until the next time the tournament was held in Mexico in 2026.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] South Korea qualified for the first time since 1954, Paraguay for the first time since 1958, Portugal for the first time since 1966, Morocco for the first time since 1970 and Bulgaria and Uruguay for the first time since 1974.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] It remains as of 2026 the last appearance of Hungary and Northern Ireland.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The following 24 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Eleven cities hosted the tournament, with a total of twelve stadiums used (two of them in Mexico City), among which were counted all five stadia that hosted the 1970 tournament.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The Azteca Stadium in Mexico City, the largest stadium used for the tournament, hosted nine matches (including the final), more than any other stadium used.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Mexico City hosted 13 total matches; the Olimpico Universitario Stadium hosted four matches (if the Mexico City suburban town Nezahualcoyotl's three matches are included, this brings the total up to 16 matches; nearly a third of all matches in this tournament).
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The hot, humid and rainy summer weather in Mexico varied from humid desert locations like Monterrey to tropical locations such as Guadalajara; but perhaps the greatest hardship the players had to contend with was the high altitude of the Mexican locations.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Mexico City, the location of the opening and final matches and the location where the most matches were played was 7,380 feet (2,250 m) above sea level and the weather there was not as hot as in other cities used in this World Cup.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] All of these venues except Monterrey were located in central Mexico, as this tournament was organized with the then-standard way of keeping teams playing in locations in close proximity to each other.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] All of the venues listed hosted knockout round matches except the ones in Nezahualcoyotl, Irapuato, Zapopan, Toluca and the Estadio Tecnologico in Monterrey.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] For a list of all squads that appeared in the final tournament, see *1986 FIFA World Cup squads*.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The first round of the finals began in Group A, where Italy were held 1–1 by Bulgaria.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Meanwhile, Argentina beat South Korea 3–1, with Diego Maradona playing a major part.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Italy and Argentina drew 1–1, Maradona and Alessandro Altobelli scoring.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] South Korea and Bulgaria also drew 1–1 in a downpour.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The final set of matches saw Argentina beating Bulgaria 2–0, and Italy narrowly defeating South Korea 3–2.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] In Group B Mexico beat Belgium 2–1, and despite being held 1–1 by Paraguay, they won the group after a further win over Iraq, 1–0.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Paraguay and Belgium also progressed after both beating Iraq and drawing with each other.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Group C pitted a strong Dynamo Kyiv-dominated Soviet Union side against the reigning European champions France.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] They drew with each other 1–1, with a goal scored by Vasyl Rats.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] France beat Canada 1–0 and finished in 2nd place in the group after beating Hungary, 3–0.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Hungary had earlier lost 6–0 against the Soviet Union, which won the group due to goal difference.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Group D saw Brazil start against Spain, winning 1–0 after the referee failed to validate a legal goal scored by Míchel.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Northern Ireland began their campaign with a draw against Algeria.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Northern Ireland were then narrowly beaten by Spain before losing to Brazil 3–0 in their final match.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] This match saw a goal from Josimar on his debut and was also the final time Pat Jennings played for Northern Ireland.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Spain qualified along with Brazil after defeating Algeria 3–0.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Denmark stormed through Group E, dubbed the group of death, with a 100 per cent record.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] They beat Alex Ferguson's Scotland 1–0 in their first game, then hammered Uruguay 6–1, with Preben Elkjær hitting a hat-trick.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Denmark beat one of the favourites to win the tournament, West Germany, 2–0 thanks to a Jesper Olsen penalty and a goal from John Eriksen.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] After losing to Denmark, Scotland took the lead against West Germany thanks to a Gordon Strachan goal, but the West Germans fought back to win 2–1.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] After a violent 0–0 draw against Uruguay, the Scots were eliminated from the tournament.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] During that game José Batista of Uruguay was sent off after less than one minute of play for a foul on Strachan, a World Cup record that still stands.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] West Germany went through to the second round despite a loss against Denmark.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Morocco topped Group F after holding both Poland and England to goalless draws, and beating Portugal 3–1.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] By doing so, they became the first African team, and only the second nation from outside Europe and the Americas (after North Korea in 1966), to reach the second round.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] In their last first-round game, with the captaincy taken over by Peter Shilton in goal, a first-half Gary Lineker hat-trick helped the reshaped side beat Poland 3–0 – although losing yet another player to a ban for the next round, Terry Fenwick receiving his second booking of the tournament.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Poland had previously beaten Portugal, and in the end the Portuguese were the only team from Group F to be eliminated in the first round.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Portugal, making their first appearance in 20 years, went on strike (in the Saltillo Affair) during the competition.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Players refused to train between their first and second games (against England and Poland) and were eliminated after a loss to Morocco in the final group match.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Belgium beat the Soviet Union 4–3, despite a hat-trick by the Soviets' Igor Belanov.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The game was level at 2–2 after 90 minutes, and in extra time Stephane Demol and Nico Claesen put Belgium 4–2 up.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Belanov scored from the penalty spot with nine minutes remaining, but neither he nor any of his teammates could find a fourth goal for the Soviet Union.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] At the Olympic University Stadium in Mexico City, the European champions France ended Italy's reign as world champions with a 2–0 victory thanks to goals from Michel Platini and Yannick Stopyra.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] In the rematch of the 1930 FIFA World Cup Final, Argentina just edged out South American champions Uruguay in Puebla thanks to a 42nd-minute strike from Pedro Pasculli.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The all-South American affair had a Diego Maradona goal disallowed.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] In Querétaro, Denmark were eliminated as they went from a 1–0 lead to a 5–1 battering against Spain; key player Frank Arnesen was suspended for the game after being sent off against West Germany in their last group match, for taking a swipe at German playmaker Lothar Matthäus.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The Danes scored first, with a Jesper Olsen penalty, but they were then taken apart by a devastating performance from Butragueño of Spain, who scored four of his team's five goals.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] At the Azteca Stadium in Mexico City, England progressed to the quarter-finals comfortably when they saw off Paraguay 3–0, while Brazil brushed aside Poland 4–0.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] West Germany had a much harder time getting past Morocco, for whom goalkeeper Badou Zaki had an outstanding game.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Morocco held out until the 87th minute, when Lothar Matthäus scored the only goal of the match with a free kick.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Mexico won 2–0 against Bulgaria with an outstanding scissor-kick goal by Manuel Negrete which is honored by a remembrance plaque at the Azteca.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] In the quarter-finals, France faced three-time world champion Brazil in Guadalajara.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Brazil were well on top in the early stages, and Careca put them one up after 18 minutes.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Five minutes before half-time, France drew level when Michel Platini scored his 41st goal after converting a cross from Dominique Rocheteau.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Brazil had a chance to regain the lead in the second half when Branco was fouled by French keeper Joël Bats in the penalty area.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Zico got up to take the kick, but Bats saved Zico's penalty.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The match went to extra time, and France finished slightly the stronger of the two sides.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] No more goals were scored, and so it was time for a penalty shoot-out.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Socrates, who had earlier missed an open goal and headed an easy chance straight into the French keeper's arms, failed with the first kick for Brazil.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The next six penalties were all converted, and then Platini fired over the bar.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Brazil were back on level terms – but not for long.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Julio Cesar struck the post with his penalty, and Luis Fernández then scored to put France through 4–3 on penalties.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Two other quarter-finals were also decided on penalties.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Jan Ceulemans put Belgium ahead against Spain in the 35th minute, but Spanish substitute Señor equalised with five minutes to go.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] No more goals were scored in extra time, and Belgium won the shoot-out 5–4.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] On the hosts' first game outside of the Azteca, Francisco Javier Cruz saw a goal disallowed as West Germany and Mexico drew 0–0 after extra time.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The West Germans eliminated the hosts 4–1 on penalties.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] As a curiosity, the German goalkeeper Harald Schumacher jumped to the right in the three Mexican penalties (stopping two of them).
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The quarter-final between Argentina and England at the Azteca featured two very different goals in the second half by Diego Maradona: the first was scored illegally, as he punched the ball into the goal past England goalkeeper Peter Shilton.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The referee did not see the handball and the goal was given as valid.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] After the game, Maradona claimed the goal was scored "A bit with the head of Maradona and another bit with the hand of God"; it became known as the "Hand of God" goal.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] For his second goal, voted "Goal of the Century" in 2002 on the FIFA website, Maradona dribbled half the length of the field past five English players before scoring.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] In Argentina, the game was seen as revenge for the Falklands War.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] In the first semi-final match, Andreas Brehme put West Germany 1–0 ahead against France in the ninth minute in Guadalajara, but the outcome remained in doubt until two minutes from time when Rudi Völler made it 2–0, and West Germany were in the final for the second World Cup in succession.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] In the second semi-final match, Maradona struck twice in the second half as Argentina beat Belgium 2–0 at the Azteca.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] France went on to defeat Belgium in the match for third place, 4–2.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] So it was to be the South American Argentina vs the European West Germany at the final at the Azteca, the second time this massive stadium would host a World Cup Final (the first in 1970).
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Jose Brown put Argentina one up midway through the first half of the final, and when Jorge Valdano scored a second for the South Americans in the 55th minute, Argentina looked to be strolling to victory.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] West Germany then staged a spirited comeback.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Karl-Heinz Rummenigge pulled one back in the 74th minute, and six minutes later Rudi Völler hit the equaliser.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] With seven minutes remaining, a pass from Maradona gave Jorge Burruchaga the chance to score the winner for Argentina.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Eight years on from their home triumph, Argentina regained the world title and 30 million people in Argentina celebrated in the streets after the final victory.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Maradona was the Golden Ball winner as the best player of the tournament, while Gary Lineker of England won the Golden Boot as the leading scorer of the World Cup with six goals.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Argentina beat West Germany for the first time and won their second World Cup.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Belgium finished in fourth place, their best finish in the World Cup until 2018, where they finished third.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Gary Lineker received the Golden Boot for scoring six goals.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] In total, 132 goals were scored by 82 players, with two of them credited as own goals.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] In 1986, FIFA published a report that ranked all teams in each World Cup up to and including 1986, based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The sponsors of the 1986 FIFA World Cup consisted out of 15 FIFA World Cup sponsors.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The official mascot of the 1986 World Cup was *Pique*, a jalapeño pepper, characteristic of Mexican cuisine, with a moustache, a Colimote sombrero, and Mexican football team colours.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] Its name comes from *picante*, a Spanish word meaning "spicy", and was also a pun on the "PK" abbreviation of the football term penalty kick.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The character caused a degree of controversy within Mexico for its ethnic stereotypes.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The official match ball of this World Cup was the "Azteca", manufactured by Adidas.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] It was the first fully synthetic FIFA World Cup ball and the elaborately decorated design was inspired by the hosting nation’s native Aztec architecture and murals.
[src:citroën-2cv/1986-world-cup] The official song of this World Cup was "El mundo unido por un balón".
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The **2019–2021 Algerian protests**, also called **Revolution of Smiles** or **Hirak** (Arabic: الحِرَاك, romanized: *al-Ḥirāk*, lit.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] 'The movement'), began on 16 February 2019, six days after Abdelaziz Bouteflika announced his candidacy for a fifth presidential term in a signed statement.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] These protests, without precedent since the Algerian Civil War, were peaceful and led the military to insist on Bouteflika's immediate resignation, which took place on 2 April 2019.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] By early May, a significant number of power-brokers close to the deposed administration, including the former president's younger brother Saïd, had been arrested.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The rising tensions within the Algerian regime can be traced back to the beginning of Bouteflika's rule, which has been characterized by the state's monopoly on natural resources revenues used to finance the government's clientelist system and ensure its stability.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Major demonstrations took place in the largest urban centers of Algeria from February to December 2019.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Due to their significant scale, the protests attracted international media coverage and provoked reactions from several heads of states and scholarly figures.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Abdelaziz Bouteflika had been president of the People's Democratic Republic of Algeria since 1999.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Two amnesties (via referendum) for former combatants in the Algerian Civil War had taken place during his presidency (1999 and 2005).
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] A complex "dirty war" between Islamic guerrillas and the government had claimed a contested number of approximately 200,000 lives between 1991–2002.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Nearly half of the Algerian population was born after the end of the conflict, amidst the din of repeated corruption scandals.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] With Bouteflika's accession to power in 1999, he began a diplomatic mission to rehabilitate Algeria's image abroad.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] He set about consolidating power, especially after his re-election in 2003.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] During his tenure as president, the power center in Algerian politics shifted from the east to west, most particularly to Tlemcen, where some became highly placed figures in the media, administration, and police.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Roughly $10 billion of public funding flowed to the city for construction projects, including a university, hotels, museums and airports. €155m was spent on a state residence, which remains incomplete.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Many of the public works contracts were given to Chinese companies, by whom local contractors were allegedly not always paid.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Oil-rich during the Arab Spring, the government was able to quiet dissent during the 2010–2012 protests with increased spending.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The constitutional revision of 2016 limited the number of presidential terms that could be served to two, but nevertheless allowed Bouteflika to seek a fifth term, because the law was not retroactive.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Since 2005, and especially after his stroke in 2013, Bouteflika's ability to govern the country was called into question: rumors of his death were frequent as he was often hospitalized, no longer spoke and made very few written statements.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In this context, some Algerians considered his announced candidacy for the presidential election, originally scheduled for 18 April 2019, 4 July 2019 or 2020, to be humiliating.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Members of Bouteflika's administration were accused of engaging in corrupt practices in several instances.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In 2010, Sonatrach, the state-owned oil and gas company, suspended all of its senior management after two of the company's vice-presidents were imprisoned for corruption.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Algeria's Energy Minister Chakib Khelil announced that the president of the company and several executives had been placed under judicial supervision.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In 2013, Khelil was also accused of receiving a bribe from a subsidiary of the Italian energy company Eni.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] According to *El Watan*, overbilling for public works and misleading descriptions of imported goods were two common corrupt practices, facilitated by cronyism at the highest levels.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 26 June 2018, Bouteflika dismissed Abdelghani Hamel as head of the national police (DGSN), despite the latter being part of his inner circle.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] This news came after one of Hamel's drivers had become a suspect in Cocainegate, which led to a general of the gendarmerie, four judges and two public prosecutors being tried for bribery.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Djamaa el Djazaïr, a large mosque under construction in Algiers, is nicknamed the Great Mosque of Bouteflika.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Though its construction was touted as an Algerian job-creator, immigrant workers did most of the work for China State Construction Engineering while living in prefab shantytowns around the construction site.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The project still came in 2.5 times over-budget.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The cost of the mosque's construction has been estimated to be between $1.4 and $2 billion.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] A doctor quoted in *Le Monde* complained that "with $4 billion [sic], 200 hospitals could have been built." Converting the mosque into a hospital has been suggested.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] For the Algerian press, it became a symbol of the mismanagement of public funds and of the "capricious megalomania" of the former President.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Broadly, cumulative grievances and aspirations were at the heart of the protest movement.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Decade-long economic stagnation, unemployment, labour market segmentation, and chronic corruption fueled discontent.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Plummeting oil and gas prices weakened the regime's capacity to continue buying off some sections of the lower classes and youth, and to contain discontent.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In December 2018, calls for demonstrations in the neighborhood of Bab El Oued against the fifth term went unheeded, except by the police, which mobilized a significant dissuasive force.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The protests were at first, following the 10 February formal announcement of Bouteflika's candidacy, limited geographically to northern Algeria.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In Khenchela, on 19 February, a giant poster of the President of the Republic was torn down from city hall and trampled.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Two days later, another suffered a similar fate in Annaba.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] This form of protest was related to the recent practice of offering gifts to a framed portrait of Bouteflika in the latter's absence.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Protests were organized via social media in major and mid-sized cities on 22 February.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Those in Algiers—where street protests had been illegal since a demonstration on 14 June 2001—were the biggest in nearly 18 years.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Smaller protests, with slogans like "There is no president, there's a poster," had been taking place in Algiers since 11 February.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 22 February, the portrait of the President was torn down from the landmark central post office.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] There are no official government numbers published, but one expert put the number of demonstrators at 800,000 on 22 February 2019.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Regularly hospitalized for "periodic medical examinations", Abdelaziz Bouteflika was admitted to the University Hospital of Geneva (Switzerland) on 24 February 2019.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Another large-scale demonstration took place on 24 February at the call of the Mouwatana movement ("citizenship"), On 28 February, a dozen journalists were arrested during protests against press censorship.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Three million people were estimated to have demonstrated on 1 March 2019, though no official figures were given.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The private channel Dzaïr News reported that one million people demonstrated across Algeria on 1 March, which was also the first time state television broadcast images of the protests.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] 183 people were injured and Hassan Benkhedda, son of former interim government president, Benyoucef Benkhedda, died of a heart attack.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 2 March 2019, Abdelaziz Bouteflika replaced his campaign director, the former prime minister Abdelmalek Sellal, who had actively campaigned for the President since 2004, by the virtually unknown Abdelghani Zaalane, a career provincial administrator.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Considered to be a response to the ongoing protests, this dismissal followed the disclosure of a recording between Sellal and Ali Haddad in which the former is heard making threats.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The deadline for submitting candidatures for the presidential election was 3 March 2019.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The idea of postponing the election was put forward.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 3 March, the candidacy of Bouteflika was filed by his campaign director, though the law stipulates that the candidate must be physically present for this process.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Another signed message announced that if re-elected, a national conference would be convened to adopt reforms as well as a new Constitution – to be approved by referendum – and that he would not take part in the next presidential election which he promised would be held early.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] After the confirmation of Bouteflika's candidacy on Sunday, 3 March, and the withdrawal of several opposition candidates, including Ali Benflis and Louisa Hanoune, an anonymous call to strike was made the next day, as well as a call to protest on 8 March.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Even before the candidacy was formalized, tens of thousands of protesters were out on the streets.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] From Sunday night to Monday morning, hundreds of protesters marched peacefully, calling his candidacy a "provocation", an "insult" and a "masquerade".
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The next day, many students boycotted their classes.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The opposition, meeting at the headquarters of the Justice and Development Front, called for candidates to withdraw from the election.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On the same day, following the example of the resignation the day before of Khaled Tazaghart, an elected representative (député) from the El Moustakbal party, & former minister Sid Ahmed Ferroukhi (FLN), resigned from the party.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Zahir Kherraz, FLN mayor of Oued Amizour, also said he did not support a fifth term.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Amar Benadouda (1931), doyen of the mayors of the country, resigned from the town hall of Guenzet.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On Tuesday, protests and student strikes continued, thousands were in the streets of Algiers, Constantine, Oran, Annaba, Bejaia, Tizi Ouzou, Bouira, Blida, Setif, or Tlemcen.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On Thursday, a thousand lawyers demonstrated in Algiers.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The "Pacifist and Civilized Walkers' 18 Commandments", written by Lazhari Labter, were widely circulated on social media prior to the 8 March demonstration.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In reaction to the Friday demonstrations, the Ministry of Higher Education and Scientific Research moved the spring university holidays forward to the next day (10 March) and extended them by two weeks in an effort to calm matters down.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 10 March, the Army Chief of Staff Ahmed Gaid Salah, close to Bouteflika, gave a speech to officer cadets saying the "army and the people had a common vision of the future".
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] This speech was front-page news in *El Khabar*.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] A 5-day general strike was begun the same day.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On Thursday, lawyers and judges were on the streets in several cities.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The protests on 15 March were estimated to have been larger than those the previous Friday.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] *The Guardian* reported that hundreds of thousands were in the streets, *La Croix* put the number at over a million.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Protesters carried a banner criticizing France's comments that the cancellation of elections should lead to a "transition of reasonable length" saying, "It's the people who decide, not France!".
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Other signs included "Macron, deal with your yellow vests" and "Elysée, stop!
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 17 March, the newly appointed Prime Minister announced the intention of forming a government of politically unaffiliated experts, which would "reflect the demographics of the Algerian society".
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Students were again in the streets on Tuesday, 18 March demanding that Bouteflika step down by the end of his term (28 April).
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The army chief of staff said that the army needed to deal with the crisis.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 26 March, in a speech given in Ouargla and covered live on Algerian television, Ahmed Gaid Salah urged the Constitutional Council to declare Bouteflika unfit.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The Council began deliberations the same day.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] When the sitting president is removed, the president of the Council of the Nation—at the time Abdelkader Bensalah—becomes acting president for a maximum of 90 days while elections are organized.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 27 March, Ahmed Ouyahia called on Bouteflika to resign.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The same day the Workers' Party announced the resignation of their elected members of the People's National Assembly.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On Friday 29 March, the Algerian authorities denied Reuters' reports that there were a million protesters in the capital, but did not put forward numbers of their own.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Bouteflika named a new government on 31 March 2019, two days before his resignation.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Investigations were opened into a dozen oligarchs who were prevented from leaving the country.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Ali Haddad's resignation from the FCE—an employers federation, which had seen a wave of recent resignations over his remarks about the protests—and his subsequent arrest at the Tunisian border were widely reported.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Bouteflika made a statement promising to step down by the end of his term, but equivocating as to the actual date.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The following day, the Army Chief of Staff (who had been appointed by Bouteflika to replace General Mohammed Lamari after his 2004 election) insisted both privately and publicly that he resign immediately, which he did.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] As provided for under Article 102 of the Algerian Constitution, Abdelkader Bensalah became acting interim President.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] His term can last for a maximum of 90 days while a presidential election is held.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] By law, he cannot participate in this election.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Tear gas and a water cannon were used repeatedly to prevent more than a thousand students chanting "*Silmiya, Silmiya*" (peaceful, peaceful) from going through the Tunnel des Facultés in Algiers on the 8th successive Tuesday of student demonstrations.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The Friday protests, of the same size as previous weeks, were more conflictual, with police blocking access to the city and parts of the city.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 16 April, the president of the constitutional council, Tayed Belaiz—one of the three Bs whose ouster protesters sought—informed the council that he had submitted his resignation.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The size of the protests on 19 April was similar to previous weeks.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Ennahar TV reported that five billionaires were arrested on 22 April 2019: four brothers from the Kouninef family, close to Saïd Bouteflika, and Issad Rebrab, the CEO of Cevital.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The head of Cevital's communications department denied the reports.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] A judge also called in the former prime minister and the current finance minister for questioning.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On Friday 26, thousands of protesters gathered in Algiers for the tenth week despite attempts by the authorities to close all entrances to the capital.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Banners such as "The system must go" and "We are fed up with you," were raised in city centre.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Earlier, Algeria's richest businessman and three other billionaires were arrested in an on-going investigation on the grounds of corruption.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] For the eleventh consecutive week, tens of thousands of people, according to al-Jazeera, demonstrated on Friday 3 May and raised banners that read: "You must go" and "Thieves you have destroyed the country".
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Protesters also continued to insist on the peaceful character of their demonstrations, chanting "Peaceful, peaceful," while marching in central Algiers.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On Saturday 4 May, the former president's younger brother, Saïd Bouteflika, was arrested along with former secret service head General Mohamed Mediene ("Toufik") and intelligence chief Athmane Tartag ("Bachir").
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 19 June 2019, Lieutenant general Salah reiterated that no flags other than the "national emblem" would be tolerated during demonstrations.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In so doing, he was targeting the Amazigh flag, a frequently-seen flyer during the Hirak (movement).
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The aim was to first obtain wide consensus on the list of mediators.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 15 September, the government announced a presidential election to take place on 12 December.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Demonstrations continued, calling for Ahmed Gaïd Salah and other members of the former Bouteflika governmental clique to resign.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The authorities blocked road entries to the capital Algiers and arrested prominent protesters in preparation for the following Friday. protesters called for a general strike each Tuesday starting 24 September.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 1 November, the metro was shut down in Algiers and trains into the city were canceled as a result of a social media campaign calling for demonstrations.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Police roadblocks also caused traffic jams.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] They rejected the 12 December election, with slogans describing it as "an election with the gangs" and as an "election organised by a corrupt power [which] is a trap for idiots" (French: *les élections d'un pouvoir corrompu est un piège à cons*).
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 15 November, the 39th successive Friday of protests included objections to the 12 December presidential election and calls for arrested protesters to be freed.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 6 December, crowds in Algiers, Constantine, Oran, and in Kabylie were massive, calling for a boycott of the elections scheduled for the following week and for a general strike starting on 8 December.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The presidential election was held on 12 December 2019, despite wide popular opposition, with a turnout of 8% according to the Rally for Culture and Democracy or 39.88% officially, with Abdelmadjid Tebboune officially elected in the first round with 58.13% of the valid votes.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] During the three days around the election, 11–13 December 1200 protesters were detained by the authorities according to the CNLD.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Later in December, the CNLD estimated that according to its records, 180 prisoners of conscience remained in prison, either under remand or serving sentences.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Gaid Salah suffered a heart attack on the morning of 23 December 2019 and was rushed to a military hospital in Algiers, where he died a few hours later.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] His last public appearance was four days earlier when he received the National Order of Merit from President Abdelmadjid Tebboune.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 2 January, 76 prisoners of conscience detained because of their protest actions were released, some of them conditionally.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 15 January, 13 detainees held in El-Harrach prison since 1 March 2019 started a hunger strike, with the aim of getting a fair trial.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Their cases had rested frozen for 10 months and their court appearances were scheduled for 16 March 2020.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In the 17 January Hirak protest marches, twenty of the first protesters to arrive in the morning were arrested in Algiers.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] As of 18 January 2020, Youth Action Rally (RAJ) estimated that a total of at least 100 Hirak prisoners of conscience were being held in Algerian prisons, while the CNLD estimated that 120 or more Hirak prisoners remained under detention.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In early February, close to the anniversary of the first protests on 16 and 22 February 2019, President Tebboune signed a decree pardoning several thousand prisoners, who were released from jail, but the Hirak protest prisoners of conscience were not included in the pardon.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 20 March 2020, Algerian protesters heeded a presidential order over the coronavirus, and the pleas of some of their own leaders, by not staging their weekly demonstration against the ruling elite on Friday for the first time in over a year.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Leading supporters of the protest movement, including imprisoned activist Karim Tabbou, human rights lawyer Mustafa Bouchachi and former minister Abdelaziz Rahabi, had urged the protesters to suspend their marches.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Abdallah Benadouda, an Algerian exile in the US with experience in Algerian public radio and private television (Dzaïr TV), started Radio Corona International 21 April 2020 to keep the Hirak flame alive during the lockdown.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Benadouda encourages comparison to pirate radio in Europe in the 1970s and has discussed government crackdown on journalists (Khaled Draini) and opposition figures (Karim Tabbou).
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 5 October, Algerian protesters marked the 32nd anniversary of a pro-democracy movement, with hundreds of protesters gathering in the streets of the capital, Algiers.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 9 October, following the rape and killing of a teenage girl, protests erupted in several cities across Algeria, decrying gender-based violence.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The body of Chaïma, 19, was said to have been discovered in an abandoned petrol station in Thenia, 50 miles east of Algiers, earlier in the month.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Chaïma's family revealed that she went missing after going out for a walk to pay her phone bill, and was subsequently stabbed, raped and allegedly burnt alive.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] A constitutional referendum had previously been announced in July that was to be held in November as a result of the protests earlier in the year, but critics said it fails to address popular concerns of overreach by the government.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] 5,000 people gathered in the town of Kherrata on 16 February to mark the second anniversary of the Hirak protest movement.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Demonstrations had been suspended because of the COVID-19 pandemic in Algeria.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 18 February, President Abdelmadjid Tebboune released 70 people who had been imprisoned for their participation in demonstrations, but that did not stop thousands from demonstrating on 22 February.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] These are the largest protests in Algeria since 2001.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The demonstrators are primarily young people who did not experience the "Black Decade".
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Women's active role in the protests was credited with minimizing violence, and marked a sharp contrast with the 1988 protests predominantly led by salafists.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] An old mother of five unemployed children told the BBC: "There's nothing for the young generation," she said.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Demonstrations also took place abroad, particularly in France, where 10,000 demonstrated in Paris on 8 March.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Originally the protesters wanted Abdelaziz Bouteflika to withdraw his candidacy for a fifth term and wanted Prime Minister Ahmed Ouyahia to step down.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In conjunction with the president's withdrawal, the protesters called more and more for democracy, liberties and the rule of law, goals which many protests argue are unrealized and which continue to attract Algerians into the street.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Yetnahaw Gaa !, often written *Yetnahaw ga3 !*, or, in Algerian Arabic, (يتنحاو ڨاع), means "they should all go" and became a rallying cry after Bouteflika renounced his run for a fifth term.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Some slogans referred to the incumbent president as "the Moroccan" because of his birthplace and his reputed membership in a shadowy second Oudja Clan.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Others, such as "bring back the commandos of the army and the BIS, there will be no fifth term" alluded to the *baltaguias*.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] By April, common slogans, placards, chants and hashtags included: "Leave means Leave" and "Throw them all out".
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Songs such as "Libérer l'Algérie", written by artists supporting the movement, "Allô le système!" by Raja Meziane and "La liberté" by Soolking, became hits with the protesters upon their release.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Cachir, an emblematic Algerian sausage, was brandished and tossed around during demonstrations as a reminder of the 2014 elections when the press reported that Bouteflika's re-election committee was increasing attendance at their meetings by handing out free sandwiches filled with the sausage.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In the protester's eyes, cachir had become a "symbol of corruption and of the 'buying of votes and souls.'" The Algerians have also employed humour and comedy to express dissent and discontent.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] "Algeria, country of heroes that is ruled by zeros", "System change ...
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In reaction to calls by Gaid Salah to apply article 102 of the constitution, so the leader of the upper house would take over with elections to be held 90 days after the presidency is declared vacant by the constitutional council, people replied: "We want the application of article 2019 ...
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] You are all going" "We asked for the departure of the whole gang, not the promotion of some of its members" "Batteries are dead so no need to squeeze them" "Dear system, you are a piece of s*** and I can prove it mathematically" "Here Algeria: the voice of the people.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Please call people's service at 07" (in reference to article 07 stipulating that the people are the source of all sovereignty).
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In Bordj Bou Arréridj, a city 200 km east of the capital Algiers, every Friday protesters have been hanging a new tifo since the fifth Friday.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Displayed on an unfinished building renamed "The People's Palace", the banners bear cartoons and slogans, and as more Algerians from other cities have been pouring in every Friday the town has been named "The Capital of the Hirak" (The capital of the popular movement).
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The idea of the tifos is borrowed from the ultras groups which, according to sociologist Mark Doidge, were political protests in the 1960s and 1970s Italy.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Although the rallies were generally peaceful, some vehicles were burned and shops were vandalized in the evening of demonstrations.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 1 March, clashes took place between the police and groups of young people throwing stones at them.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] 41 arrests were recorded on 23 February and 45 on 1 March including five men caught trying to haul away a safe.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The police reported that "the majority of the people arrested were under the influence of psychotropic or hallucinogenic substances".
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Until 1 March 2019, public television, radio, and press totally ignored the demonstrations, while private television channels linked to the establishment dealt with them in a limited way.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] A boycott campaign was launched against the media.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The editor-in-chief of Channel III, Meriem Abdou, resigned on 23 February as a protest against the treatment of the movement on the government-run radio station.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] A hundred journalists and the NGO Reporters Without Borders publicly denounced the censorship practiced by the Algerian executive.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] When state TV channels did begin mentioning the protests, they were critical of the protesters and did not refer to their motives.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In contrast, private print media and news sites reported widely on events from the beginning.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Despite the opening of the audiovisual media to competition in 2011, off-shore channels can be shut down at any time because of their precarious legal status.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] One foreign media outlet, Al Jazeera, has been banned from Algeria since 2004.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 4 March, Nadia Madassi, Canal Algérie's nightly news anchor for the past 15 years, resigned because she had been required to read a letter attributed to the president on the air.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 5 March, Echorouk and El Bilad were sanctioned by the Ministries of Communication for having covered the demonstrations, and were cut off from advertising by the ANEP (national publishing and advertising agency).
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Women created the feminist collective Femmes algériennes pour un changement vers l'égalité on 16 March 2019, which pioneered the *feminist square* in the Friday Algiers protests to strengthen the political role of women in the protests.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Citizens' associations and individuals created the Dynamiques de la société civile alliance on 15 June, which was later joined by trade unions, with the aim of coordinating proposals to reorganise the political structure of the Algerian state.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 26 June, political parties and the Algerian League for the Defense of Human Rights created the Forces of the Democratic Alternative alliance with similar aims, including the organising of a constituent assembly for a new political system with an independent judiciary.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The 13-person dialogue panel, the *Instance nationale de dialogue et de médiation*, was created and led by Karim Younes.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The dialogue panel and the holding of the election were widely criticised by the protesters and by the *Forces of the Democratic Alternative*, who stated that the arrests of protesters for political reasons and the lack of basic conditions of democracy were conditions unsuitable for an election.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Citizens' groups to monitor the detentions of protest participants and call for their release were formed.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The Network for fighting against repression was created on 1 June 2019 to call for the release of prisoners including Louisa Hanoune, the first woman to run for President of Algeria, and Hadj Ghermoul, a member of the Algerian League for the Defense of Human Rights.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The National Committee for the Liberation of Detainees (CNLD) was created on 26 August 2019.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In late December, several weeks after the presidential election won by Abdelmadjid Tebboune, the CNLD had documentation of 180 "Hirak" prisoners under remand or sentenced, and saw "no sign" of the government ceasing its frequent arrests of the protesters.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 25 January 2020, 400 people from various political parties and citizens' associations participated in Algiers in a meeting organised by *Forces of the Democratic Alternative*.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The conclusion of the meeting was to hold another meeting to organise the detailed methods and rules for implementing a democratic transition during which existing "illegitimate" institutions would be dismantled and for organising a constituent assembly.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 11 March, it was announced that President Bouteflika would not seek re-election; that Prime Minister Ahmed Ouyahia had resigned and been replaced by Interior Minister Noureddine Bedoui; and that the April 2019 presidential election was postponed indefinitely.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Inquiries were announced into "corruption and illicit overseas capital transfers" on 1 April 2019.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Ali Haddad was arrested trying to cross the border into Tunisia after liquidating stock worth €38m.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On the same day, Bouteflika promised to step down by the end of his term on 28 April.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 2 April 2019, Bouteflika resigned as president, after being pressured by the military to step down immediately.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Under Article 102 of the Algerian Constitution, he was succeeded as interim President by the President of the Council of the Nation, Abdelkader Bensalah, who was ineligible to run in the election for a successor, which according to law had to be held in the next 90 days.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The presidential election was finally held on 12 December 2019, despite wide popular opposition.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The Rally for Culture and Democracy estimated the turnout in the election at 8% of the eligible electorate, interpreting the low turnout as a result of wide rejection of the election.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The official turnout was 39.88%, with Abdelmadjid Tebboune officially elected in the first round with 58.13% of the valid votes, leaving it unnecessary to hold a second round of the election.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 7 May 2020, the preliminary draft of the constitutional amendment was published.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] In addition, the Hirak is inscribed in the preamble of the Constitution and the army is authorized to participate in theaters of operation abroad.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Finally, the National Independent Election Authority (ANIE) is constitutionalised, the presidential third of the Council of Nation is abolished and the possibility of legislating by ordinance during parliamentary recess is abrogated.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 8 September 2020, the final draft of the constitutional amendment was published.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] It revokes both of the vice-president post and the abolition of the presidential third of the Council of Nation.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] The weekend after Bouteflika stepped down, protesters in Sudan called upon the army to take their side against sitting president Omar al-Bashir.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Despite the state of emergency and the emergency courts the President created to treat the protests, demonstrators staged a sit-in in the public space outside the Khartoum headquarters of the Armed Forces.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] On 28 February 2019, the economist Omar Benderra asserted that a deep separation exists between civil society and the Algerian government, which outlawed street protests twenty years ago, and which he wrote is controlled by "warlords".
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Public opinion, Benderra continues, is suspicious of official government communication and has also begun to show signs of frustration with spiritual leaders urging the people to stay off the streets.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Fahad Nabeel from the Centre of Strategic and Contemporary Research was less optimistic about the movement's success, suggesting that either the *pouvoir* or the military would consolidate control.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Algerian journalist Ghada Hamrouche doubted whether it was even possible to hold elections as promised by the interim president.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Hamrouche considered elections within the current constitutional set up a diversion.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Ahmad Al-Sholi thinks that the Algerian regime is very entrenched and enjoys a good leverage generated by the revenues of the oil industry, a 'surplus' with which it could "co-opt large swaths of the population and oppositional forces.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] Despite the plummeting oil prices in the world market, the regime argues Al-Sholi, could attract foreign investment and still refill its coffers.
[src:citroën-2cv/2019-2020-algerian-protests] International reactions were cautious; most countries and international organizations remained silent until 5 March.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The Citroën **2CV 24 Hour Race** is an annual 24-hour endurance race for Classic Citroën 2CVs, and is traditionally held in August regularly at the Snetterton Circuit in Norfolk.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The race is organised by the Classic 2CV Racing Club, with BARC and MSV.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] From 2014 to 2016 the 24hr race was held at the Anglesey Circuit in North Wales.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] This was due to development of the track, including the Pit Lane area, to enable a 24hr race licence to be granted.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The first 2CV 24hr race was held in 1990 at Mondello Park a short distance from Dublin, and remained at the circuit until 2003 when it moved to Snetterton in Norfolk.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The 2020 Citroën 2CV 24 Hour Race was held at Snetterton Circuit on 28–30 August.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] It was the only 24 Hour race to take place in the UK in 2020.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The 2020 race was won by 2CV Team Lion 1 with drivers Pete Sparrow, Alec Graham and David O'Keeffe in 662 laps.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] Pete Sparrow set the fastest lap on the new Snetterton 200 for Club Class 2CV of 1.48.382.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] Crisis@TeteRouge were 2nd (659 laps) and Team Twin Snails 3rd (655 laps).
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The 2019 Liqui Moly Citroën 2CV 24 Hour Race at Snetterton Circuit was won by Team Gadget Racing with Drivers Ainslie Bousfield, Simon Clarke, Lien Davies, Tom Perry in 701 laps.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] Crisis TeteRouge were 2nd (699 laps) and 2CV Team Lion 1 3rd (689 laps).
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] Pete Sparrow won the 2CVParts.com Championship for the 8th time.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The 2018 Liqui Moly Citroën 2CV 24 Hour Race at Snetterton Circuit was won by Team Beacon Downe with drivers Richard Gardiner, Louis Tyson, Kris Tovey & Peter Rundle in 708 laps.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] Dan Willans Coaches Team ECAS were 2nd (697 laps) and Team Gadget Racing 3rd (691 laps).
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] Pete Sparrow won the 2CVParts.com Championship for the 7th time.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The 2017 Liqui Moly Citroën 2CV 24 Hour race at Snetterton circuit was won by Team LION 1, with drivers Pete Sparrow, Alec Graham and David O’Keefe in 706 laps.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] Team ECAS were 2nd (699 laps) and Team Rebellion 3rd (691 laps).
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] Lien Davies won the 2CVParts.com Classic Racing Championship in a Team Gadget Racing car.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The 2016 24 Hour race at the Anglesey circuit was won by 2CV Team LION, with drivers Pete Sparrow, David O'Keeffe and Alec Graham.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The 2CVParts.com Championship was won by Lien Davis in a Team Gadget Racing car.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The 2015 24 Hour race was won by Team SeaLion, with drivers Pete Sparrow, Jon Davis, Alec Graham and David O'Keeffe.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] In the same car, Pete Sparrow won the 2CVParts.com Championship for the 6th time.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The 2014 24 Hour race was won by Team SeaLion, with drivers Pete Sparrow, Jon Davis, Peter Rundle and Paul Rowland.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] Pete Sparrow in the same car won the 2CVParts.com Championship for the 5th time.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The 2013 24 Hour race was won after 717 laps, by Team Stinky, with drivers Neil Thompson, Neil Savage, Christer Hallgren and Chris Yates.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The car's remarkable reliability was the key to the win as other teams succumbed to various mechanical issues.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The race remained dry throughout the 24hrs.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The 2012 race was won again by Rent Boys Racing with the same driver line up, and the car once again prepared by Mark Turner.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] No other team had won this race three times consecutively, any driver line up achieving a hat trick in 24-hour endurance racing is unusual, and only ever been achieved twice previously.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] Making this achievement one of the most impressive in British motorsport in recent history.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The 2011 race was won by Rent Boys Racing with an unchanged driver line up however for this year the car was prepared by Mark Turner with a second car now part of the team (Rent Boys Racing 2).
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The race was on the Snetterton 200 Circuit.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] In 2010 the race was won by Rent Boys Racing team with Alec Graham, Meyrick Cox and Nick Paton driving.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] In 2009 the race was won by the Tete Rouge team with David O'Keeffe, Phil Myatt, Gary Adnitt and Sammie Fritchley driving.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] They completed 566 Laps (the race was stopped for 5 and a half hours due to Fog).
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] In 2008 the race was won by Team Gadget Racing with Wayne Cowling, Ainslie Bousfield, Steve Panas and Simon Clarke driving.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] In 2007 the race was won by Team ECAS with Richard Dalton, Gary Byatt, Phil Myatt, Edward Mason driving.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] In 2006 the race was won by Tete Rouge 1 with Christian Callender, Pete Sparrow, Simon Turner, Simon Leith driving.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] In 2005 the race was won by Tete Rouge 1 with Paul Robertson, Pete Sparrow, Simon Turner, Colin Whiteley driving.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] In 2004 the race was won by Dead End Racing with Phil Myatt, Edward Mason, Graham Wallace driving.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] They completed 740 laps and their Best Lap was 1.47.826.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] In 2003 the race was won by car 80, BAPS Racing. with Ainslie Bousfield, Gary Adnitt, Steve Panas and Mick Storey.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] They completed a shortened 507 laps due to fog stopping the race.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] Of note was that the Fastest Lap of Race – 1.49.202 (was achieved by 'The Stig' from BBC TOP GEAR - Ben Collins).
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] Due to the participation of the Television Programme, this race was covered in Series 2, Episode 10 of Top Gear.
[src:citroën-2cv/2cv-24-hour-race] The Circuit de Spa-Francorchamps also hosts a 24-hour 2CV race.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The city expanded quickly after the construction of a new wharf in 1931, followed by its designation as the capital city of the then-French colony in 1933.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The completion of the Vridi Canal in 1951 enabled Abidjan to become an important sea port.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan remained the capital of Ivory Coast after its independence from France in 1960.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In 1983, the city of Yamoussoukro was designated as the official political capital of Ivory Coast.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] However, Abidjan has officially been designated as the "economic capital" of the country, because it is the largest city in the country and the centre of its economic activity.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Many political institutions and all foreign embassies continue to be located in Abidjan as well.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The Abidjan Autonomous District, which encompasses the city and some of its suburbs, is one of the 14 districts of Ivory Coast.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] According to oral tradition of the Tchaman as reported in the *Encyclopedic Dictionary of Côte d'Ivoire*, the name "Abidjan" results from a misunderstanding.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Legend states that an old man carrying branches to repair the roof of his house met a European explorer who asked him the name of the nearest village.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The old man did not speak the language of the explorer, and thought that he was being asked to justify his presence in that place.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Terrified by this unexpected meeting, he fled shouting "*min-chan m'bidjan*", which means in the Ebrié language: "I just cut the leaves." The explorer, thinking that his question had been answered, recorded the name of the locale as *Abidjan*.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] A slightly different and less elaborate version of the legend: When the first colonists asked a native man the name of the place, the man misunderstood and replied "*M'bi min djan*": "I've just been cutting leaves".
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan was originally a small Atchan fishing village.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In 1896, following a series of deadly yellow fever epidemics, French colonists who had initially settled in Grand-Bassam decided to move to a safer place and in 1898 chose the current location of Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The settlers were followed by the colonial government, created in 1899.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] But then nearby Bingerville became the capital of the French colony, from 1900 until 1934.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The future Abidjan, situated on the edge of the *lagoon n'doupé* ("the lagoon in hot water"), offered more land and greater opportunities for trade expansion.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The wharf in Petit Bassam (now Port-Bouët) south of town quickly overtook the wharf of Grand-Bassam in importance, and became the main point of economic access to the colony.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In 1904, the rail terminus was located in the Port-Bouët area of Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Starting in 1904, when Bingerville was not yet complete, Abidjan became the main economic hub of the colony of Ivory Coast and a prime channel for distributing products to the European hinterland, particularly through the Lebanese community, which was increasing in importance.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Henri de Fougères became governor of French Sudan in 1924, and remained governor until his death in 1931.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] One of the main streets of Abidjan still bears his name.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In 1931, Plateau and what would become Treichville were connected by a floating bridge, more or less where the Houphouët-Boigny Bridge stands today.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The year 1931 also saw addresses begin to be assigned to the streets of Abidjan for the first time.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The addressing project was temporarily concluded in 1964, under the leadership of Mayor Konan Kanga, then badly redone American-style in 1993.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan became the third capital of Ivory Coast by a 1934 decree, following Grand-Bassam and Bingerville.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The decision to designate Abidjan as the capital spurred from its railroad that would connect the North and South regions of the Ivorian colony.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Several villages in Tchaman were then deserted.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The leader of the Tchaman community can still be found in Adjame ("center" or "meeting" in Tchaman), north of the Plateau.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] South of the Plateau district (the current central district of the city of Abidjan), the village of *Dugbeo* was moved across the lagoon to Anoumabo, "the forest of fruit bats", which became the neighborhood of Treichville (now known as Commikro, city of clerks).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Treichville was renamed in 1934, in honour of Marcel Treich-Laplène (1860–1890), the first explorer of the Ivory Coast and its first colonial administrator, considered its founder.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Instead of Dugbeyo, is the current Treich-Laplénie Avenue, the bus station and water lagoon buses in Plateau, and the Avenue Charles de Gaulle (commonly called Rue du Commerce).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The city was laid out like most colonial towns, on a grid plan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Le Plateau ("m'brato" in Tchaman) were inhabited by settlers.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In the north, the city was inhabited by the colonized.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The two zones were separated by the Gallieni Military Barracks, where now there is the current courthouse.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] City spaces were often segregated between French colonists and Ivorian natives.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Near the port, originally named Boulevard de Marseille, settlers became defensive and stole a street sign of a famous street of Marseille renamed the street Canebière, a sand track.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] This is the legend behind the first Blohorn oil mills, in Cocody and a racetrack was built in the south of the city.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In Le Plateau in the 1940s, the Bardon Park Hotel was built, the first air-conditioned hotel working in francophone Africa.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Under the *Pacte Colonial* (Colonial Pact), Abidjan served as a port city that would connect the colonial hinterlands that produced raw materials to the industrial centers of France.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The construction of the 15m-deep Vridi Canal in 1950 aided in this endeavor by connecting the Ebrié Lagoon to the sea.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] By the late 1950s, Abidjan became the financial center of West Africa, challenging the dominance of Dakar.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In 1958, the first bridge to connect Petit-Bassam Island with the mainland was completed.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] During World War II, France's Vichy government completed construction of the Port in Abidjan to counter British influence.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] After the war, France competed with other harbors in the Gulf of Guinea, and due to increased foreign interest in the capital city, placed protectionist policies on imports, foreign consulates, and U.S. building contracts.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The Abidjan city council elections of 1945 sparked the beginnings of the nationalist movement that challenged France's authority.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] When Ivory Coast became independent in 1960, Abidjan became the new country's administrative and economic center.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The axis south of Treichville, towards the international airport and the beaches, became the heart of European and middle-class Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The city saw considerable population growth in the decades following independence, expanding from 180,000 inhabitants in 1960 to 1,269,000 in 1978.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan's skyline dates back to the economic prosperity of this period.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] New districts such as the upmarket Cocody were founded during this period; built to a large extent in a colonial style, Cocody has since become home to Ivory Coast's wealthy classes as well as expatriates and foreign diplomats.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The district is home to the embassy of France, Hotel Ivoire (which for a long time, was the only African hotel to have a skating rink), and, since 2009, the largest U.S. embassy in West Africa.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Paul's Cathedral, designed by Italian architect Aldo Spirito, began with the 1980 groundbreaking by Pope John Paul II and was completed in 1985.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] From the 1980s, Abidjan's fortunes declined as a result of negligence on the part of officials as well as corruption and general degradation.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In 1983, the village of Yamoussoukro became the new political capital of Ivory Coast under the leadership of President Félix Houphouët-Boigny, who was born in Yamoussoukro.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] From 2002 to 2007 and especially from 2010 to 2011, Abidjan suffered from the consequences of the First and Second Ivorian Civil Wars.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In November 2004, armed conflict broke out between French forces and Ivorian forces loyal to Laurent Gbagbo after the Ivorian Air Force attacked French peacekeepers in northern Ivory Coast.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] After France destroyed Ivory Coast's air capabilities in retaliation, pro-Gbagbo groups staged riots and looting in Abidjan and targeted French homes, schools, and businesses.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] French peacekeepers moved into the city to calm the situation.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Other crises during the first civil war period include the case of the *Probo Koala* in 2006, in which disposed products caused thousands of residents to seek medical attention.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Ivory Coast's civil conflicts seriously impacted the security situation in Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Amidst the anti-French riots in November 2004, 4,000 prisoners in Abidjan escaped from the country's largest prison.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan was one of the main theaters of the 2010–2011 Ivorian crisis and the site of major demonstrations against incumbent president Gbagbo, including one on International Women's Day in 2011 that saw several demonstrators killed by Gbagbo's forces.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Civil postwar violence persisted in urban districts with high territorial control by Ggabo's supporters.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Districts became associated with specific political attributes, which Ggabo's forces used to target residents in Abobo and Yopougon.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Ethnic homogeneity in segregated neighborhoods is suggested to have enabled such territorial turmoil.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The end of the crisis came with Gbagbo's capture in Abidjan in April 2011, following a major offensive by forces loyal to election winner Alassane Ouattara with support from France and the UN.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Overtime, the intensity of postwar violence has decreased.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In 2025, a major overhaul of names from the colonial era will be reorganized to more African names.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan lies on the south-east coast of the country, on the Gulf of Guinea.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The city is located on the Ébrié Lagoon.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The business district, Le Plateau, is the center of the city, along with Cocody, Deux Plateaux (the city's wealthiest neighborhood and a hub for diplomats), and Adjamé, a slum on the north shore of the lagoon.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Treichville and Marcory lie to the south, Attecoube, Locodjro, Abobo Doume and Yopougon to the west, and Île Boulay is located in the middle of the lagoon.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Further south lies Port Bouët, home to the airport and main seaport.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan experiences a tropical wet and dry climate, according to the Köppen climate classification (Köppen climate classification: **Aw**), closely bordering a tropical monsoon climate.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan has nonconsecutive rainy seasons (precipitation above 60 millimetres (2.4 in) with a long rainy season from March to July and a short rainy season from September to December, and three dry months (January, February and August).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Precipitation is abundant during the summer months, except for August, due to activation of the Benguela Current, which reduces the precipitation total throughout the month.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The Benguela Current also lowers the mean temperature during August, making it the coolest month of the year, averaging 24.5 °C (76.1 °F).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan has two additional dry months (January and February).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan is generally humid, with average relative humidity above 80% throughout the year.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The annual temperature would increase by 1.8 °C (3.2 °F), and the temperature of the coldest month by 1.9 °C (3.4 °F), but the temperature of the warmest month would be 3.4 °C (6.1 °F) higher.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] According to Climate Action Tracker, the current warming trajectory appears consistent with 2.7 °C (4.9 °F), which closely matches RCP 4.5.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Moreover, according to the 2022 IPCC Sixth Assessment Report, Abidjan is one of 12 major African cities (Abidjan, Alexandria, Algiers, Cape Town, Casablanca, Dakar, Dar es Salaam, Durban, Lagos, Lomé, Luanda and Maputo) which would be the most severely affected by the future sea level rise.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] It estimates that they would collectively sustain cumulative damages of US$65 billion under RCP 4.5 and US$86.5 billion for the high-emission scenario RCP 8.5 by the year 2050.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Since sea level rise would continue for about 10,000 years under every scenario of climate change, future costs of sea level rise would only increase, especially without adaptation measures.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The 10 communes of the former City of Abidjan are traditionally divided into northern Abidjan and southern Abidjan, with the Ébrié Lagoon separating both halves of the city.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Towns near Abidjan include Jacqueville, Grand-Lahou and Dabou in the west; Sikensi, Tiassalé, Agboville, Adzopé and Alépé in the north; and Grand-Bassam to the east.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The towns (or sub-prefectures) of Anyama, Bingerville, Brofodoumé and Songon are within the Abidjan Department, which is co-extensive with the autonomous district.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Formerly managed by the French colonial administration, Abidjan became a municipality (commune) in 1956, divided into administrative areas by lagoons.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Its first municipal council was elected on 18 November 1956, and the first mayor in the context of the Loi-Cadre of 1956 was president Félix Houphouët-Boigny.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In 1980, the municipality of Abidjan (*commune d'Abidjan*) was transformed into the City of Abidjan (*Ville d'Abidjan*), and its territory was divided in 10 communes.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] A city council and mayor of the City of Abidjan elected by the population oversaw the entire city, whereas 10 municipal councils also elected by the population managed each commune.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Dioulo Emmanuel was elected mayor of the City of Abidjan on 30 November 1980.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In 2001, the City of Abidjan was disbanded and replaced by a larger Autonomous District of Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The autonomous district overlaps the Abidjan Department, which was established in 1969 and has had its current boundaries since 1998.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The district is made up of the 10 communes of the former City of Abidjan, and of 4 outlying sub-prefectures: Anyama, Bingerville, Brofodoumé, and Songon.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Since the 2000s, the built-up area of Abidjan has largely expanded into these 4 formerly rural sub-prefectures.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] As a result of the creation of the Autonomous District of Abidjan in 2001, the post of Mayor of City of Abidjan was replaced by that of District Governor, appointed by the head of state.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The position has been occupied by Ibrahim Bacongo Cissé since 2023.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Each of the ten communes of Abidjan has its own municipal council, headed by a mayor.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The last municipal elections were held in 2018.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The sub-prefectures of the autonomous district also have their own mayors and councils.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The communes of Abobo, Adjamé, Attécoubé, Cocody, and Plateau are located north of the Ébrié Lagoon (hence the name "Abidjan North").
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] This is the continental part of Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The commune of Yopougon straddles the lagoon, with part lying north and part south of that body of water.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The communes of Treichville, Koumassi, Marcory, and Port-Bouet in Abidjan are south of the lagoon.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Blokosso and Locodjro villages are included within the city and maintain cultural identity in urban areas.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The Université Félix Houphouët-Boigny was founded in 1964.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In Ivory Coast, the enrollment rate is 74% and access to secondary education is limited by an entrance assessment at the 6th stage after which one-third of students are allowed to continue their studies.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] 24% of the student population resides in Abidjan, which comprises 20% of the total population.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan is the location of the main educational institutions in Ivory Coast.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] These include the Lycée Classique d'Abidjan, the Lycée Sainte-Marie de Cocody, Lycée garçon de Bingerville, and Mami Adjoua the Lyceum.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The Blaise Pascal Abidjan school is a French school – a school who has signed an agreement with the AEFE.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Recently the Lycée International Jean-Mermoz re-opened which was initially called College International Jean-Mermoz, founded by Pierre Padovani.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The Institution suffered from a devastating war and was forced to close.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The city also hosts a campus of the HEC Paris business school.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The majority of Ivorian government institutions are still located in Abidjan and have not been transferred to the political capital, Yamoussoukro.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The President's office is in Cocody, and the parliament, the Constitutional Council, the Supreme Court, and the Chancellery of the National Order are all in Le Plateau.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Under the presidency of Laurent Gbagbo (2000–11), efforts were made to give effect to the project of making the political capital Yamoussoukro in Côte d'Ivoire.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] This goal continues to be the consensus of the country's political leaders.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Government offices are located in Le Plateau in the administrative district of Abidjan, Boulevard Carde or Angoulvant Boulevard (near the Cathedral of St.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Paul of Abidjan), or elsewhere in the great buildings of the town.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The instability of the 2002–2007 civil war and 2010–2011 crisis saw foreign peacekeeping forces stationed in Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The United Nations Operation in Côte d'Ivoire (UNOCI), established in April 2004, has its headquarters at the former Hotel Sebroko in Attécoubé.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] While the size of the force has been reduced since the end of the 2011 crisis, UNOCI's mandate was extended in 2013 and again in 2015.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The force remains authorized to maintain up to 5,245 troops, 192 observers, 1,500 police and eight customs officers in the country.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] France's peacekeeping operations in Ivory Coast continued under the aegis of Operation Unicorn until 2015 and then as the French forces in Côte d'Ivoire from 2015 onward.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In 2014, French defense minister Jean-Yves Le Drian announced that Abidjan would be reinforced as the entry point for France's military presence and counterterrorism operations in the Sahel region.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] After al-Qaeda militants targeted beachgoers at Grand-Bassam in March 2016, the French government announced it would increase its troop deployment in Côte d'Ivoire from 500 to 900.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] French soldiers are based in Port-Bouet as well as at the Abidjan airport.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In 2007, Pierre Laba's comedy film *Permanent Danger* explored the laxity of the police against banditry in major African cities, specifically in Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan is divided into districts, each of which has a police station.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The municipal police and national police are separate.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] All police are trained at the National Police Academy in the town of Cocody.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] They are recruited by competitive examination held by the police administration.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The Force and CECOS accompany the police.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The main base of the gendarmerie is at Agban (commonly Adjamé).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] A training school is in Cocody and the city.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Since 2000, Ivory Coast has experienced a sharp rise in drug trafficking.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Drug dens arise mainly in informal settlements and there has been a recent spike in demand among unemployed youth and Ivorian vagrants.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The Ivorian police increasingly focus on the fight against trafficking and drug use in the district of Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] A report by the Office of the UN says West Africa plays an increasingly important role in the transit of cocaine between Latin America and Europe.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In May 2007, seven drug houses were dismantled and 191 people arrested including a military officer.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan is home to Port-Bouet, one of the six French military bases that still exist in Africa (Dakar, Libreville, Bouar CAR, N'Djamena and Djibouti).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Thousands of people live there, around the 43rd BIMA which is permanently in place in accordance with established defence agreements on 24 April 1961 linking the two countries.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Diplomatic missions in Ivory Coast are mostly located in Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The African Development Bank (ADB), the largest financial institution in Africa, is headquartered in Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The 2021 census recorded Abidjan's population as 6,321,017.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] As Abidjan is inhabited by people from a wide array of different ethnicities, French is commonly spoken in the metropolitan area, which is the third largest French speaking metropolitan area in the world after Kinshasa and Paris.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Colloquial Abidjan French has even appeared, which has a different pronunciation and some slang words different from standard French.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan is recognized as one of the few areas in Africa where French (colloquial Abidjan French) is truly a native tongue, along with Libreville, Gabon.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The District of Abidjan's population was 6,321,017 at the 14 December 2021 census, up from 4,707,404 at the 15 May 2014 census.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Population increase, lower in the 2000s due to the economic crisis and Ivorian Civil War, has picked up in the 2010s to levels unseen since the 1980s thanks to the rapid economic growth experienced by Abidjan after the return of peace in 2012.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Many inhabitants come to live in Abidjan for employment and better standards of living.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] By 1950, Abidjan had just exceeded a population of 50,000 (at the end of 1948).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Reaching a population of a million by the end of 1975, the city grew at a rate of 10 to 12% per year, doubling every six or seven years.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] However, this growth underwent a sharp decline due to the crises of the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In the last 20 years of the 20th century, the growth rate dropped to 3–6%.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Birth rate growth was supplemented by migration, with the influx being substantial and the outflow only partly offseting the arrivals.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The migration, prior to the census of 1988, contributed a growth of about 80,000 with 50,000 people from within Ivory Coast, and about 30,000 from abroad per year.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] From within Ivory Coast, the migration pattern was dominated by Akan (South-east, 48%), then Mandé (North-west, 24%) and Krou (South-west, 20%).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] From abroad, the migration was Burkinabes (30%), Malians (22%), Ghanaians (19%), Nigerien (11%), and Guineans (9%).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Of the non-African migration, Lebanese migration was highest, followed by European migration, with the French being largest of this latter group.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] All in all, people of non-African origin represent 3% of the total population of Abidjan, which remains the highest in the region.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The traditional language of the city's region is Ebrié.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Since the colonial period, the official language in Abidjan and throughout Côte d'Ivoire has been French.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Another form of spoken French in Abidjan is *Nouchi*, a highly informal variety used as adolescent slang.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The historical lingua franca, still spoken and understood by most of the trading population of Abidjan, is Dioula.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The city is home to Ivorians from throughout the country and about sixty vernacular languages are spoken, such as Attié, Baoulé, Bété, and Wobé.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan is surrounded by more than thirty villages where Baoulé and Ébrié are still commonly spoken.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Some traditional medicine establishments sell traditional drugs in the street.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] There are numerous health centers, pharmacies and pharmacopoeias.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The city has more than fifty clinics, and over sixty specialist locations (veterinary, dermatology, dental, optometry, motherhood, psychology, pediatrics, etc.).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Modern districts like Plateau or Cocody have developed similar to those in Europe with the construction of large office towers and apartment buildings between the 1970s and the mid-1980s.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The CCIA building (Abidjan International Trade Center Building), a skyscraper, was completed in 1982.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Traditional neighborhoods like Treichville or Marcory maintained the system of "concessions" where housing is adjacent to the plant and an area of several houses, within the normal organization and multi centuries-old African villages.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The district of Cocody is also home to many single-storey wooden villas, surrounded by vast gardens of lush vegetation, fed by the heavy rains that water the city.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Wealthier inhabitants constructed villas in imitation of Greek temples in this district.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In addition, many houses were built on stilts on the edge of the Ébrié Lagoon.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The town hall, a fine example of modernist architecture, was designed by architect Henri Chomette.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The urban network is disrupted, as Abidjan has seen its population double every seven years since 1945.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Rural people are attracted by the opportunities of the city.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Abidjan represents 45% of city dwellers in Ivory Coast and 20% of the overall population.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The city is by far the country's largest, dwarfing the second-largest city, Bouaké (which had 542,082 inhabitants in 2014) as well as the political capital, Yamoussoukro (207,412 inhabitants).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Since the 2006 Probo Koala toxic waste dumping incident, significant efforts have been made to address waste management issues in Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] In 2006, a contract was signed between China and Ivory Coast: a Chinese company handling urban waste and industrial plans to treat all waste district this transformation also create daily cleaning.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] French nongovernmental organisation ACTED rolled out a three-part project across three districts of Abidjan in 2016, establishing street cleaning, waste collection and hygiene training.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] ACTED spokesperson Jérémy Lescot described the project as "a fine success".
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The last transportation upgrade in Abidjan led to the repaving of certain roads in the capital in 1994.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Since May 2007, the company Ageroute (Road Management Agency) is undertaking major operations in Abidjan and Anyama relating to badly damaged roads, suffering from lack of maintenance, heavy rain and protests.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] It is also addressing the gutters and unpaved roads.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The District and BNETD plan to rehabilitate and construct 400 to 500 miles (640–800 kilometres), providing them with a quality to last 15–20 years of life.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Improvements include the rehabilitation of roads in Abidjan and Anyama, construction of drains, the tarring of gravel roads and sanitation of the city by the construction of sewers.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] The principal stock exchange of Ivory Coast and the other seven countries of the Union Économique et Monétaire Ouest Africaine (UEMOA), Bourse Régionale des Valeurs Mobilières (BRVM), is located in Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Air Ivoire had its head office in Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p01] Prior to its dissolution, Air Afrique was headquartered in Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The region near the lagoons is the most industrialized region of the country.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Major industries include food processing, lumber, automobile manufacturing, textiles, chemicals, and soap.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Its industries are mainly in construction and maintenance with the presence of major international groups: the furnace SETAO, Colas, Bouygues, Jean Lefebvre, and Swiss Holcim.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] There are textile industries with the packaging of cotton in the north both for export or for on-site processing of cloth, canvas, batik clothing and miscellaneous.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The textile sector is very dynamic, and represents 15.6% of net investment, 13% of turnover and 24% of the value added in Ivorian industry.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] There are several offshore oil wells in operation (Côte d'Ivoire is an oil producing country), which leads to the presence of a chemical industry with oil refineries, and an oil port.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The city also has a large wood processing plant at the port by river from the forests of central Canada.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] It exports natural mahogany, peeled wood, plywood and chipboard for the past two centuries.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Food industry mainly include: the production of palm oil, bergamot and Seville oranges.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] In the west, rubber is processed as well as manufacturing beverages from pineapples, oranges and mangoes, producing robusta coffee: Côte d'Ivoire is the third largest producer, behind Colombia and Brazil and processing cocoa, it is the largest producer in the world ahead of Ghana and Indonesia.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] (37% of cocoa and 10% of coffee products undergo at least one first local processing).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is also the first African tuna port for the European market.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] This generated 3,000 salaried jobs and is an important source of foreign exchange.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] As in all countries of the Third World developing countries, much of the city's economy lies in what economists describe as informal economy with its many "odd jobs".
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The development of tertiary industry, with the establishment of international commercial banks and the increasing number of service companies of all types, appears to be the trend of recent years.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is the main financial center of French West Africa.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The seat of the common stock exchange of West Africa (BRVM) is located in Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] BRVM is mainly dominated by Ivorian firms.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The thermal power plant Azito, built in 1997 in partnership with EDF, located on the Yopougon on the edge of the lagoon and facing Ébrié Island Boulay, alone provides 300 MW.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Two other power plants, built in 1984 and 1985, are installed in Vridi.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The production, which increases steadily, and gas storage are provided by two state companies: PETROCI and GESTOCI.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] A small industry of renewable energy production has also developed.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The city has a powerful fixed telephone network of 450,000 lines (in 2004) managed by *Côte d'Ivoire Telecom*.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Broadband Internet connections, leased lines and ADSL are powered by various providers: Aviso Ivory Coast Telecoms.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is home to all the representatives of international financial institutions: World Bank, International Monetary Fund, African Development Bank, BOAD, etc.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Banking Commission of WAEMU regional stock exchange securities subsidiaries of major international banks: BNP Paribas, General bank, Crédit Lyonnais, Citibank, JPMorgan Chase & Co., Barclays, etc.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Sixteen national banks (SGBCI, BICI, etc.) maintaining a network of 170 branches, seven financial institutions and more than thirty insurance companies make a financial competitive Abidjan that animates the entire West Africa.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Trains on the line to Ouagadougou run from several stations in the city, the most important being in Treichville.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Ferries link Treichville, Abobo-Doumé and Le Plateau.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Félix-Houphouët-Boigny International Airport serves the city.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Work on a new metro system has begun, with the beginning of service expected in 2028.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] SOTRA (Abidjan Transport Company) ensure urban transportation in Abidjan via bus, taxi and luggage Line Express.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] SOTRA has announced the start of work for the use of light rail to Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The project has three phases at a cost of 125 billion CFA francs for a long loop of 32 km.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] There are two kinds: the taxi-meter (red), which can travel throughout the city, and woro-woro (yellow and green, blue or orange depending on the commune), which are limited to a neighborhood.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Port Bouet Airport has a large capacity that allows it to accommodate all existing large aircraft.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is located an hour's flight from all the capitals of the sub-region.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is served by major airlines in the direction of the great capitals of the world.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Headquarters of the former multinational African Air company, Abidjan airport had nearly 2,070,000 passengers in 2017.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The District has several paved streets and boulevards linking the towns between them and the District across the country.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan has a network of urban bypasses.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] River transport is already consistent with fishing spots and many "boat-buses" connecting the various neighborhoods of the city thrives plan lagoon.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is also the bridgehead of the country's only highway linking the city to the administrative and political capital, Yamoussoukro.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan has one of the biggest ports in the sub-region (West Africa).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] It is a container transshipment port and was opened in 1951 in the presence of the Minister of Overseas and Colonies at the time, François Mitterrand.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The 15 m deep Vridi Canal, where boats with large draughts can dock in the deep-water port.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Ivory Coast is in the Franc Zone (where the currency is CFA francs), as part of the West African Economic and Monetary Union (WAEMU).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is the economic centre of both the Côte d'Ivoire and of the whole region, including Burkina Faso and Mali; this is mainly because of its deep-water port.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The road network in Abidjan (5,600 km asphalted in 1995, compared to 1,000 km in 1970), which covers the whole region, effectively increases its port activity as 50% of the business from Burkina Faso, Mali and Niger pass through it.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan receives the bulk of the country's industrial activity; its port alone receiving 60% of ivory park industry.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan has ambitions of oil-production—off-shore production and especially refining and distribution.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] In 1995 the port received 12 million tonnes of traffic, of which 5.5 million tonnes were petroleum products.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Exports include coffee, cocoa, timber, bananas, pineapples, and manganese.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Alassane Ouattara Bridge, completed in 2023, is the 5th bridge over the Abidjan lagoon.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The two-halves of the city, Northern Abidjan and Southern Abidjan, are joined by the Houphouët-Boigny, the Charles de Gaulle and the Henri Konan Bédié bridges.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The two former bridges, built in the 1950s and 1960s respectively, are located between Treichville and Le Plateau.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The Général-de-Gaulle Bridge extends over the immense Valéry Giscard d'Estaing Boulevard which leads to the airport.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Both bridges are often congested, especially during rush hour or on the occasion of police and military roadblocks.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] A third 1.5 km (0.93 mi) toll bridge and expressway, the Henri Konan Bédié Bridge between Cocody and Marcory was completed in December 2014.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Project construction began in the second half of 2012 and required the relocation of several homes and businesses opposite the Mille Maquis (the noted restaurant *la Bâche bleue* was moved).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] According to data reported by the African Development Bank, 2,499 persons were impacted by the bridge construction and were relocated and compensated.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] A fourth 1.4 km (0.87 mi) 8-lane toll bridge between Yopougon and Plateau was built between 2018 and 2024.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] A fifth 630 m (690 yd) 4-lane toll-free bridge, the Alassane Ouattara Bridge between Cocody and Plateau, was built between 2019 and 2023.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The city is the foothold for the region's only railway: the Abidjan-Ouagadougou line, with stations in Treichville, Abobo and Adjamé.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] This line only has two trains, the *Gazelle* and the *Bélier*, and links the two capitals in about 40 hours.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The most recent project in Abidjan is the Abidjan Metro which is promised by the Ivory Society of Railroads (SICF).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The development of infrastructural projects has been envisaged, including a suburban train system in Abidjan which is estimated to cost almost 100 billion CFA francs.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] This suburban train system would link the North-West to the East and North of the city.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The project extends over 25 km of railway tracks which as of 2011 were used by the operator Sitarail, a subsidiary company of the Bolloré group.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The infrastructural works (tracks, electrification, and civil engineers) have been estimated at 40 billion CFA francs, financed by the State of Ivory Coast and backers (World Bank and the French Development Agency).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] In addition, a BOT concession contract would be given to a private operator, over 20–30 years, to operate the network.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] This operator will be in charge of the acquisition of railway materials, workshop renovation and the implementation of an organisational system.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The concession contract has been estimated to be around 60 billion CFA francs.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Its nicknames, such as "Manhattan of the tropics", "Small Manhattan" or "Pearl of the lagoons", explain the city's unpredictable and triumphant image.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] With its accommodation facilities – such as the Golf Hôtel – and sporting facilities, its lively night life, transport and communication lines as well as its impressiveness, it is the perfect city for business tourism.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan also has beaches around the lagoon, with palm and coconut trees, in the Vridi area, which are very popular at weekends with the picturesque sight of the pineapple and coconut sellers.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Nevertheless, the rip-tides which affects practically the whole of the Gulf of Guinea's coast, means that in this area swimming is not usually allowed.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Generally, in Cote d'Ivoire, tourism has never really been developed as an economic industry; the country is not much of a common holiday destination.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Converted in 1926, this park has 3,000 hectares and ancient "sacred wood" lies at the entrance to the city, in the Attécoubé community, which has been conserved as a relic of the first forest which surrounded the lagoon in the past.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] A tarmaced road goes straight to the lake at the heart of the park and trails go throughout it.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The park is inhabited and there are coffee and cocoa plantations.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] At the edge of the park, a small river serves as a wash-house where the *fanicos*, laundry men, work after collecting the laundry from the whole of the city.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] It is one of the 'small jobs' which exist in Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The district has an abundance of night-clubs, maquis, out-door areas, and go-go bars.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] These entertainment platforms provide a musical 'pipeline' encompassing mainly DJs, Coupé Décalé and Zouglou, and, in lesser amounts, other local and international varieties.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Formerly containing only local traditional varieties, Congolese music and Western music, Abidjan's night life has experienced a positive cultural disruption in its music since the start of the 2000s, with the arrival of Coupé Décalé.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] This musical genre was introduced in 2002 by Douk Saga and La Jet Set, with the help of Sagacité, created a phenomenon which has not stopped spreading and reaching out to the hot nights in the capitals of the sub-region.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] It has given a globally identifiable cultural identity to entertainment 'made in Côte d'Ivoire'.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The very popular Zouglou additionally benefits "Wôyô" spaces; furnished and dedicated so that the most famous, the Internat at Fitini's and the Lycee at Vieux Gazeur's, attract 'zouglouphiles' the whole weekend.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Treichville, with its many maquis, discothèques, and jazz clubs, used to be the liveliest area in the city, but since the end of the 1990s Youpougon, Marcory, and Cocody have taken over this role.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is a turntable for West African music, and a major producer of musical art in Africa.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The city attracts the majority of musicians from the Côte d'Ivoire mainly because of its many dance clubs, which allow artists to make their debut and express themselves, record companies and national media.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Here are a few examples of the most popular artists to have made their debut in Abidjan: Alpha Blondy, Aïcha Koné, the group Magic System, Meiway, and Tiken Jah Fakoly, as well as Gadji Celi, Chantal Taiba, Nayanka Bell, DJ Arafat.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] In the 1980s, South African musician Miriam Makeba relocated to Abidjan when she was not allowed back into the country, as did the Congolese singer Tshala Muana.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Since the 1990s, Abidjan has had a significant variety of musical styles being exported throughout Africa and the West.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] These are Zoblazo, Mapouka, Zouglou and, since 2002, the Coupé-Décalé; the popularity and great variety of these dances make the city a kind of African dance and musical trend capital.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The Democratic Republic of the Congo formerly held this title, with rumba, soukous and then ndombolo.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is also considered the reggae capital of Africa.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Most mass media in Côte d'Ivoire can be found in Abidjan.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] The National Council for Audio-visual Communication (CNCA) is the regulating authority of audio-visual material in Côte d'Ivoire.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] Radiodiffusion Television Ivoirienne (RTI) is the radio and television broadcasting authority for Côte d'Ivoire; it is financed by licence fees, publicity and grants.
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] RTI has four television channels and two radio stations: *La Première* (non-specialised), *TV2*, *RTI Music TV*, *RTI Sport TV*, *Radio Côte d'Ivoire*, and *Fréquence 2* (non-specialised radio).
[src:citroën-2cv/abidjan-p02] *Radio Jam* is a private radio station in Côte d'Ivoire and is most listened to by young people.
